AGI - A high official of Hamas accused Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu> of reporting to the starting point the negotiations for the release of Israeli hostages held in Gaza. Haaretz writes it. The official told the Qatari newspaper The New Arab that Netanyahu did this to earn time. "The hostage families must know that the last round of negotiations is the last chance to bring back their children," the official warned. According to the United States, however, the agreement between Israel and Hamas would be close >.&nbsp; Discussions are taking place to reach a ceasefire agreement for the hostages in Gaza. Israel and Hamas are close enough to an agreement to fill the differences, assured the White House spokesman, Karine Jean-Pierre, aboard Air Force One, while President Joe Biden is flying to Wisconsin. Biden - informs the White House - has confidence in the fact that his team will help the negotiations.
&nbsp;
Hamas remained firm on his position with regard to a proposal for a truce and maintained its approval. In a statement, a member of the political office of Hamas, Izzat El-Reshiq. Reshiq's comments arrived while Cairo hosts new talks for the ceasefire in which Hamas delegations, Israel, the United States and Qatar participate in an attempt to conclude an agreement. In Cairo he returned the director of the CIA, William Burns, who had met Israeli Premier Benjamin Netanyahu in Tel Aviv.
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, the Israeli authorities destroyed about 50 houses belonging to Bedouin in the Negev desert. AFP journalist reported it. Israel's national security minister, Itamar Ben-Gvir, says they were "illegal constructions." The bulldozers paved the houses in the village of Wadi al-Khalil, triggering anger among the members of his community of 500 people. "There are more than 500 people here. Now children and women have nowhere else to go," said resident Sleiman Abu Asa. Israel considers the houses built in Wadi al-Khalil illegal. Ben-Gvir is "illegal constructions." Their destruction was "an important step. The police will fight whoever takes over the land and try to build on the ground." Before the creation of Israel in 1948, the Negev desert housed about 92,000 Bedouins. But only 11,000 remained within the borders of Israel after the 1948 Arab-Israeli war, according to Adalah, a defence group for Arab minorities. Today there are about 300,000, half of which live in the city and half in villages not recognized by Israel, according to Adalah. These villages lack basic services, such as waste collection.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2 US Secretary of Defense Austin confirms: "in pause supply of weapons to Israel"</h2>
U.S. Secretary of Defense Lloyd Austin is the first U.S. high official to publicly confirm that he has paused a transfer of arms to Israel > for concerns related to the military operation in Rafah, writes Haaretz. "We are currently reviewing some short-term security aid. In the context of current events in Rafah". He told a senate committee. Austin said that the United States was clear from the outset that Israel must account for civilians in Rafah.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2 The ambassador of Israel to the UN, disappoints the stop of weapons > </h2>
The Israeli ambassador to the UN, Gilad Erdan, said he did not believe that the United States would stop providing weapons to Israel, but he called Washington's decision to suspend some shipments of "very disappointing" weapons, even frustrating. The President of the United States, Joe Biden, "can't say that he is our partner in the aim of destroying Hamas while on the other hand delaying the means to destroy Hamas," said Erdan in an interview with the Israeli channel Channel 12 News.
&nbsp;
<h2>United Airlines, no flights to Tel Aviv until June></h2>
United Airlines will cancel its daily flights to Tel Aviv until 5 June.&nbsp; The airline announced it. "We continue to monitor the situation closely and make decisions on the next flights with particular attention to the safety of our customers and crews," said United in a note. The airline also added that its second daily flight to Tel Aviv will be cancelled until June 19.
&nbsp;
<h2>Oms, hospitals in southern Gaza have fuel for three days
The southern hospitals of the Gaza Strip have only three days of fuel > said the head of the World Health Organization (Oms), > because of the closure of border crossings in Rafah>. Despite international objections, yesterday Israel sent the tanks to the overcrowded southern city of Rafah and closed the nearby crossing with Egypt, which is the main access channel for aid to the Palestinian territory besieged. "The closure of the border crossing continues to prevent the United Nations from carrying fuel. Without fuel, all humanitarian operations will stop. The closure of the border also prevents the delivery of humanitarian aid to Gaza," says General Manager, Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus on X. "The hospitals in southern Gaza have only three days of fuel, which means that the services could soon stop." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
<h2>Hamas: new common pit in Al-Shifa, exhumed 49 bodies</h2>
The Hamas> government in the Gaza Strip has identified a new common pit > from which 49 bodies have already been exhumed in the Al Shifa hospital. The authorities of Gaza state that rescue teams continue to dissuade the bodies and expect to find "new bodies" in the common pit, the third found in the hospital center from which about 400 deaths have already been recovered, according to a statement. During operations at the hospital, Israel claimed to have killed some 200 alleged militants and questioned more than 800 suspects, including identifying about 500 members of Hamas and Palestinian Islamic Jihad, including senior officials. So far, according to Hamas, seven common pits were found in the Gaza Strip hospitals, three of which in Naser, three Khan Yunis (south) and another in the Kamal Adwan hospital (north).
